- [ ] Avoid inventing new cryptographic primitives
- [ ] Use standardized, vetted algorithms (e.g., AES-256, RSA-OAEP, SHA-256)
- [ ] Prefer well-established protocols (TLS 1.3, OAuth 2.0, JWT)
- [ ] Don’t roll your own hash functions, ciphers, or MACs
- [ ] Base64 encoding is not encryption; use proper encryption schemes
- [ ] Don’t implement custom symmetric encryption or decryption
- [ ] Avoid homegrown public-key cryptography implementations
- [ ] Don’t create your own digital signatures or verification logic
- [ ] Use trusted libraries (OpenSSL, libsodium, NaCl, etc.)
- [ ] Prefer authenticated encryption (GCM, CCM) over separate encryption + MAC
- [ ] Don’t mix encryption and hashing without proven authenticated modes
- [ ] Avoid custom key derivation functions; use PBKDF2, scrypt, or Argon2
- [ ] Don’t hardcode secrets or keys into the application logic
- [ ] Use secure random number generators for key generation
- [ ] Protect keys with access controls and secure storage
- [ ] Regularly audit third-party crypto libraries for updates and vulnerabilities
- [ ] Consult cryptographic standards (NIST, IETF, ISO/IEC) when unsure
- [ ] Test against known attacks (e.g., timing attacks, side-channel leaks)
- [ ] Don’t optimize away security concerns for performance
- [ ] Document choices clearly and justify them against established best practices